Some sites, bless their geographical hearts, can't be contained by a single county. The Marlette Lake Water System, for instance, sprawls across [Carson City](/Carson_City,_Nevada), [Storey County](/Storey_County,_Nevada), and [Washoe County](/Washoe_County,_Nevada). The Applegate-Lassen Trail has a similar wanderlust, touching [Humboldt](/Humboldt_County,_Nevada), [Pershing](/Pershing_County,_Nevada), and [Washoe](/Washoe_County,_Nevada). Then there's the Derby Diversion Dam, which inconveniently sits in both [Storey](/Storey_County,_Nevada) and [Washoe](/Washoe_County,_Nevada). And let's not forget the [Virginia City Historic District](/Virginia_City,_Nevada), a prime example of a place that simply refused to be confined, straddling [Storey](/Storey_County,_Nevada) and [Lyon County](/Lyon_County,_Nevada). It's almost as if history itself has no respect for arbitrary lines on a map.

Take a look at the [Nevada Governor's Mansion](/Nevada_Governor%27s_Mansion) in [Carson City](/Carson_City,_Nevada). A rather stately, if predictable, addition. Or the [Humboldt River Bridge](/Humboldt_River_Bridge), one of the last of its kind, a concrete arch-deck survivor. It’s a testament to a time when things were built to last, unlike most of what passes for infrastructure now.

The [Eureka Locomotive](/Eureka_Locomotive), a relic in [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada), and the [Esmeralda County](/Esmeralda_County,_Nevada) courthouse in [Goldfield, Nevada](/Goldfield,_Nevada), perched on [U.S. Route 95](/U.S._Route_95_in_Nevada), are just two examples. They stand as silent witnesses to eras that are long gone, their stories etched in brick and steel.

### Notes

*   The Marlette Lake Water System, a rather ambitious piece of engineering, has the audacity to extend into three distinct administrative areas: [Carson City](/Carson_City,_Nevada), [Storey County](/Storey_County,_Nevada), and [Washoe County](/Washoe_County,_Nevada). The Applegate-Lassen Trail, a path trod by pioneers and dreamers, also crosses county lines, weaving through [Humboldt](/Humboldt_County,_Nevada), [Pershing](/Pershing_County,_Nevada), and [Washoe](/Washoe_County,_Nevada) counties. Furthermore, the Derby Diversion Dam, a critical piece of water management, finds itself situated in both [Storey](/Storey_County,_Nevada) and [Washoe](/Washoe_County,_Nevada) counties. And then there's the [Virginia City Historic District](/Virginia_City,_Nevada), a place so historically significant it couldn't be contained by a single county, existing in both [Storey](/Storey_County,_Nevada) and [Lyon County](/Lyon_County,_Nevada). It's as if history itself refuses to be neatly compartmentalized.

